\begin{abstract}
Traditional educational assessments fail to capture the true ability of learners by presenting identical questions regardless of individual competency levels. This paper presents an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that dynamically evaluates student responses and adjusts question difficulty in real time using a fully LLM-driven pipeline. Building upon the multi-agent competency-building framework of Outay \textit{et al.} \cite{outay2024}, we adapt the Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model to a question-based adaptive testing context, reinterpreting its agents---the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA)---as LLM-powered reasoning modules. The system is orchestrated through CrewAI, deploying three specialized agents powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash: an MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA), a Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA), and an Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA). A dual-layer architecture ensures UI responsiveness through synchronous rule-based fallback while a background multi-agent pipeline provides AI-driven analysis. Questions are generated dynamically by the LLM, eliminating reliance on pre-calibrated Item Response Theory models and static item banks. A design-level analysis demonstrates logical consistency across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.
\end{abstract}

