\section{System Architecture}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Assessment Workflow}
The system follows a per-question adaptive loop across 20 questions per session. For each question, the student's selected answer and response time are captured. The MCQ Evaluator Agent (SOLMA) determines correctness; the Difficulty Predictor Agent (SOLPA) classifies current question difficulty; the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (SOLTA) synthesizes results and recommends the next difficulty. Three cognitive domains are supported: Reasoning, Aptitude (aliases: Quantitative Aptitude, Quant), and Verbal Ability (aliases: Verbal, English), with topic normalization enforcing a controlled vocabulary.

\subsection{Architecture Overview}
The system is a full-stack web application using Django 4.2 (Python) with MySQL, organized into five layers. The \textbf{Presentation Layer} (Bootstrap 5.3, vanilla JavaScript) handles question display, answer input, and a 20-minute countdown timer, with a fullscreen enforcement gate via the browser Fullscreen API and \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} for auto-submission on tab closure. The \textbf{Controller Layer} (Django views) coordinates the test lifecycle, implements the synchronous rule-based difficulty fallback, and spawns asynchronous agent threads. The \textbf{AI/Agent Pipeline Layer} runs the CrewAI pipeline (SOLMA$\rightarrow$SOLPA$\rightarrow$SOLTA) in a background daemon thread communicating with Gemini 2.5 Flash. The \textbf{Question Generation Layer} invokes Gemini via the \texttt{google-generativeai} SDK to generate MCQs on-the-fly with a strict JSON schema. The \textbf{Data Layer} uses three MySQL-backed models: \texttt{StudentTestResult}, \texttt{QuestionPerformance}, and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}.

\subsection{APOT Model Adaptation}
The original APOT model \cite{outay2024} follows a cyclic Assess, Predict, Oversee, and Transit process managed by LSAA, SOLMA, SOLPA, and SOLTA. Fig.~\ref{fig:apot_model} illustrates the original APOT cyclic model. In our adaptation, the \textit{Assess} stage maps to the MCQ Evaluator Agent implementing \textbf{SOLMA} by monitoring answer correctness. The \textit{Predict} stage maps to the Difficulty Predictor implementing \textbf{SOLPA} by classifying question difficulty. The \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} stages jointly map to the Adaptive Overseer implementing \textbf{SOLTA} by synthesizing analyses and determining transitions. The \textbf{LSAA} function is embodied by domain-aware question generation and multi-domain competency tracking.

