\section{Methodology}
% -------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Input Representation}
For each MCQ response, the system constructs a structured input string:

\begin{verbatim}
Question: <question text>
Correct Answer: <correct option>
Student Selected Answer: <student option>
Time Taken by Student: <seconds> seconds
\end{verbatim}

This captures factual correctness and response efficiency. Per-question timing is measured client-side via \texttt{Date.now()} differencing, with a default of 30 seconds when omitted.

\subsection{Agent Prompt Design}
Each agent's behavior is governed by \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory} fields functioning as the system prompt for Gemini. For SOLPA, the backstory encodes the time-correctness heuristic eliminating IRT parameter estimation. For SOLTA, it encodes the full bidirectional transition table aligned with the ZPD \cite{vygotsky1978}.

\subsection{Robustness Mechanisms}
The system employs: API key validation returning canned ``Medium''/``Medium'' on failure; retry logic with backoff of $(attempt+1) \times 2$ seconds for transient errors (503, 429, 500) up to 3 retries; stub fallback questions on total failure; and thread-safe DB connection cleanup in background threads.

\subsection{Session Management}
Each session is identified by a UUID linking transient \texttt{request.session} state with the durable \texttt{StudentTestResult} record. Status transitions follow: \texttt{in\_progress} $\rightarrow$ \texttt{completed} (submit) $|$ \texttt{auto\_submitted} (beacon) $|$ \texttt{expired} (exit). Fullscreen enforcement blocks the UI until opt-in. A skip-revisit mechanism defers questions for later completion.

