\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
% -------------------------------------------------------

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework \cite{outay2024} in a fully LLM-driven adaptive testing context. By mapping SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), and SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) to three CrewAI agents powered by Gemini 2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is realized through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.

The dual-layer architecture demonstrates that production-grade adaptive testing can coexist with computationally intensive LLM pipelines. Design-level analysis confirms complete transition-space coverage, logically consistent behavior, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision.

Future work will focus on: (1)~user studies to validate LLM-predicted difficulty against expert annotations; (2)~extending LSAA with explicit learning-style profiling; (3)~integrating session-level memory for cross-question tracking by SOLTA; (4)~prompt optimization to reduce output variability; (5)~comparing LLM-based decisions against IRT ground truth; and (6)~deploying for concurrent multi-user sessions with instructor dashboards.

